Trying to wrap this up ASAP which changes the economics of affine (and all private/user-deployed chutes) quite a bit for both the user and for miners here: https://github.com/rayonlabs/chutes-api/pull/55

Basically, private/user-deployed chutes will incur the standard hourly rate based on the node selector they specify, and costs are controlled via:
- max_instances (don't create more than this many instances)
- shutdown_after_seconds (shut down the chute this many seconds after the last request)
- scale_threshold (if utilization based on currency exceeds this ratio, scale up, if instance count < max_instances)

The compute units for these instances (as well as for jobs) will be based on number of seconds * gpu count * compute multiplier from node selector * 16 (meaning, it's the equivalent compute units of running a popular public chute that has concurrency of 16 and is 100% utilization)

For any custom/private/user defined chute, there is also a flat rate deployment fee defined as 3 times the hourly rate based on the node selector.

For the affine miners, they will have to pay the hourly rate for the chute, meaning we probably may end up with fewer total affine models hot at any given time, but also probably more careful selection of images, node selectors, etc. They will automatically "share" the chute with the affine developers and when they call these private chutes, the user who called the private chute incurs a cost which is then added to the actual miner's balance to offset their hourly cost (e.g. if they pay $1.00 for the instance but affine vali uses $0.5 in inference, the net effect is affine vali has 0.5 subtracted from balance and affine miner has 0.5 subtracted from balance via 1.0 removed and 0.5 from affine vai added net 0.5). 

In other words, running an affine chute will incur excellent incentives for the miners here on chutes, and the miners on affine will have more skin in the game as far as actually paying for usage in a more feasible/economical way compared to per million token pricing which we can't really sustain.

Once the economics make more sense for every party involved on the affine models I am more than happy to spin down that temp miner.

Prompt logging is disabled in all of the sglang/vllm docker images we build, traffic is encrypted to/from miners, etc. We don't store or log any data, other than user ID and metadata about the metrics/duration/etc. for billing and incentive purposes (but we also don't store IPs for example). The best guarantees will come with TEE, which, among other things, also includes:
- root users/physical access to machine won't matter, memory inside VM (which runs chutes) is encrypted
- filesystem integrity check/verification with full attestation (any tampering of files causes root encrypted drive decryption to fail) + fs-verity etc. which you can check against ubuntu packages
- admission controller to verify all chutes are running the correct image (via cosign verify)
- policies to prevent exec into pods, etc.

So we don't store anything, but until TEE is rolled out we can't *guarantee* the prompts aren't visible to admins on the underlying hardware for a brief moment while plain text (must be decrypted locally on the node to actually perform inference).

The sglang/vllm templates are open source in the `chutes` repo you can see the logging is disabled, and the API server is open source in the `chutes-api` repo, to see we don't collect or log there.

@chutes・64 New `chutes-audit` version is available, with much needed performance updates and a couple fixes.

https://github.com/rayonlabs/chutes-audit/pull/8
Be sure to check out the recommended machine specs: https://github.com/rayonlabs/chutes-audit/blob/main/README.md#recommended-machine-specs

Highlights:
- Convert invocations table in DB to partitioned table
  - each hour of audit data is it's own table so the performance of new data processing is very consistent regardless of total record count
  - old data is simply cycled out with a table drop to avoid need for expensive DELETE then periodic vacuum analyze
- Rewritten queries allow for parallel seq scans across partitions without (most) indices (meaning fewer indices = faster write perf)
- Fixed discrepancy where private invocations/compute units were included in score calculations from invocations on top of the instance audit calc method
- Multiprocessing for data transforms to actually make use of the multiple cores
- Tweaks to postgres server command startup to enable more workers / RAM for performance

This requires a full reset of the audit system from scratch, so you can either just wait to set weights again until it's caught up, or run this in parallel on another machine with the `config/config.yml` updated to set_weights false while it catches up, then spin down the old one, update the config to set weights on the new one, and restart.

Upgrade procedure:
```
docker compose down
docker compose build auditor
docker volume rm chutes-audit_postgres_data
docker compose up -d
```
I tested this on two different nodes, and the initial load times were 7 hours 32 minutes on one, and 6 hours 46 minutes on the other.
